hand mind voice arts at stanford university presented by sica home search this site arts enews subscribe featured archive gallery hand mind voice jesse rodin with carolann buff victoria chang clare robinson and eric tuan performed from the chigi codex a music manuscript from c 1500 noted for its colorful illustrations and its clear and legible musical notation as part of the hand mind voice symposium what were melodies made of for medieval singers how did choirboys clerics and composers conceptualize pitch for them the answer was obvious they used the so called guidonian hand a mnemonic system developed in the eleventh century that assigns each note a physical place on the left hand but while we have a good understanding of the hand's theoretical underpinnings we know precious little about how it was used in part because we moderns so rarely engage with it in practical contexts through scholarly presentations a demonstration of the hand in action and a roundtable discussion the hand mind voice symposium sought to fill the gap between theory and practice to grasp how musicians thought about pitch before the age of the keyboard jesse rodin with carolann buff victoria chang clare robinson and eric tuan performed from the chigi codex a music manuscript from c 1500 noted for its colorful illustrations and its clear and legible musical notation as part of the hand mind voice symposium stanford humanities center website jonathan poto sica photographer 2010 2011 home calendar gallery news visiting artists grants organizations facilities plan a visit about sica students faculty staff make a gift volunteer login press sitemap contact connect twitter facebook vimeo flickr 2011 stanford university all rights reserved local user login
